### Code Review: Bugs, Security Issues, and Fixes
The provided code has critical functional bugs, data integrity gaps, and severe security flaws. Below is a detailed breakdown, followed by corrected code:

---
## 1. Identified Issues
### Bugs (Functional/Data Integrity)
| Issue | Impact |
|-------|--------|
| Lying deleted count | The function returns `ids.length` as the number of deleted records, but this is never accurate. It does not account for non-existent ids, already deleted records, or invalid ids, leading upstream logic to assume all deletes succeeded when they did not. |
| Sequential database round-trips | Runs a separate network call to the database for every id. For 1000 ids, this causes 1000 round-trips instead of 1, leading to extreme performance degradation at scale. |
| No transaction for partial failure protection | If any delete fails mid-loop, all prior successful deletes are permanently committed, leading to inconsistent state (only some records deleted with no way to roll back automatically). |
| Missing input validation | The function does not validate that `ids` is an array, or that all elements are valid id types (e.g. integers, UUIDs matching your schema). Invalid input will throw cryptic runtime errors. |

### Critical Security Issues
| Issue | Impact |
|-------|--------|
| IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference, OWASP Top 10) | The DELETE query only filters by `id`, with no check that the requesting user owns or has permission to delete the target records. An attacker can pass any arbitrary id to delete other users' data. |
| No limit on id array size | The function accepts any length of ids, allowing attackers to pass tens of thousands of ids to launch a DoS attack against your database (lock the records table, overwhelm resources). |
| (Risk of future SQLi if refactored poorly) While the original code uses safe parameterization for individual ids, ad-hoc refactors to bulk delete that interpolate ids directly into query strings would introduce critical SQL injection flaws. |

---
